<h1>1 Project Summary	</h1>
<p>
This paper serves as succinct documentation for the Uncovering CUNY’s
Audiovisual Heritage Project (UCAVH), for which Bronx Community College,
Archives & Special Collections (BCC) is a participant. The paper aims to clarify
issues and specifications that are unique to the preservation efforts for the
Hall of Fame for Great Americans Collections (Call # LD3885.H3 A5), in which
15.5 hours of recorded content was migrated from an obsolete carrier to an
accessible digital format.
</p>
<h2>1.1 Uncovering CUNY’s Audiovisual Heritage</h2>
<p>
UCAVH  is a multi-year project that aims to digitize, describe, and make
accessible the videotape collections held in archives across the CUNY network.
The project is spearheaded by CUNY-TV and makes use of its in-house digitization
equipment and OAIS-based digital repository. The project is funded by the
Council for Library and Information Resources’ <em>Digitizing Hidden Special
Collections and Archives: Enabling New Scholarship through Increasing Access to
Unique Materials</em>.  Readers are encouraged to browse the project's dashboard
for more extensive details and documentation about the UCAVH project: <a
href="https://github.com/cunytv/UncoveringCUNYTV/blob/main/README.md">https://github.com/cunytv/UncoveringCUNYTV/blob/main/README.md</a>.
</p>
<h2>1.2 Bronx Community College, Archives & Special Collection</h2>
<p>
Thirty-five audiovisual objects from the Hall of Fame for Great Americans
collection were selected for the UCAVH project (of these, only 26 were
digitized).
</p>
<p>
The recordings are related to the Hall of Fame for Great Americans, an outdoor
sculpture gallery in Gould Memorial Library. Most of the recordings are on ¼”
open reel audio, with 5 recordings on ¾” U-Matic tape. The content documents the
ceremonies inducting individuals into the Hall of Fame.
</p>
<p>
These materials were not initially part of the grant application but folded into
the project in May 2021. The tapes were received by Kelly Haydon in Feburary of
2022 and returned to Cynthia Tobar in June 2022.
</p>
<h2>1.3 Responsibilities</h2>
<p>
CUNY-TV agrees to digitize the collection mentioned above and return the
following before the project’s end:
</p>
<ul>
<li>35 audiovisual objects submitted for preservation
<li>26 Archival Information Packages (AIP)
<li>1 Spreadsheet of descriptive and preservation metadata
<li>1 Preservation Report
<li>21 Automated transcription files (for audio)
<li>5 Automated caption files (for video)
</li>
</ul>
<p>
CUNY-TV will store the AIPs - the preservation master file, digital derivatives,
pertinent technical metadata, and file fixities - in the long-term digital
repository on LTO tape. Bronx Community College is welcome to retrieve files by
contacting CUNY-TV <a href="mailto:archive@tv.cuny.edu">archive@tv.cuny.edu</a>.
</p>
<p>
The minimum responsibility of Bronx Community College to the Uncovering CUNY’s
Audiovisual Heritage Project is to publicly post the descriptive metadata prior
to the Fall of 2022, the end of the grant cycle. Public domain metadata is a
requirement of CLIR. The metadata could be presented in a finding aid or the
description of the videos, so long as it is discoverable. Otherwise,
administrative, storage, access, description, and outreach can be folded into
current BCC workflows and practices for digital video content.
</p>
